data.content:
# .NET Framework → .NET 8 Migration: `EventProcessor`

## Critical Issues in the Original Code

| Issue | Why it breaks on .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Works but is [obsolete](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.threading.thread.interrupt) and unreliable |
| `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` | Hand-rolled producer/consumer — replaced by `Channel<T>` |
| Race condition | Multiple `Enqueue` calls between `WaitOne`/`Reset` lose items — only one `Dequeue` per signal |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _processingTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _processingTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        // ReadAllAsync drains all available items and awaits new ones.
        // Replaces the ManualResetEvent + lock + Queue pattern.
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        // TryWrite on an unbounded channel always succeeds.
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async ValueTask StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _processingTask is null)
            return;

        // Signal no more items — ReadAllAsync will complete after draining.
        _channel.Writer.Complete();

        // Give the loop time to finish gracefully.
        using var shutdownCts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
        try
        {
            await _processingTask.WaitAsync(shutdownCts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Graceful drain timed out — cancel the loop.
            await _cts.CancelAsync();
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) => Console.WriteLine($"Processed: {item}");
}
```

## Key Migration Decisions

### 1. `Channel<T>` replaces `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock`
Thread-safe, backpressure-aware, zero-lock reads. Also **fixes the original race condition** where rapid `Enqueue` calls between `WaitOne`/`Reset` caused lost items.

### 2. `CancellationToken` replaces `Thread.Abort()`/`Interrupt()`
`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8. Cancellation tokens are the cooperative cancellation primitive — `ReadAllAsync(ct)` exits cleanly when cancelled.

### 3. `Task.Run` replaces `new Thread(...).Start()`
Uses the thread pool instead of dedicating an OS thread. If you need a dedicated long-running thread (rare), use:
```csharp
Task.Factory.StartNew(() => RunLoopAsync(ct), ct,
    TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning, TaskScheduler.Default).Unwrap();
```

### 4. `IAsyncDisposable` for cleanup
`StopAsync` drains gracefully with a timeout, then cancels — no abrupt termination.

## Quick Pitfall Reference

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| Forgetting `Writer.Complete()` | `ReadAllAsync` never finishes — process hangs on shutdown |
| Blocking in `Handle()` | Starves the loop; offload CPU-heavy work or use bounded channel + multiple consumers |
| Using `Channel.CreateBounded` without handling `WaitToWriteAsync` | `TryWrite` returns `false` under backpressure — callers must handle it |
| Mixing sync-over-async (`_processingTask.Wait()`) | Can deadlock in UI/ASP.NET contexts — always `await` |
